Next, we look at the overlap sizes, calculating the query and subject length

dat$query.length <- dat[,19] / (dat[,5] - dat[,4] + 1)
dat$subject.length <- dat[,19] / (dat[,14] - dat[,13] + 1)

Most of the Potrs are fully contained

plot.multidensity(list(query=dat$query.length,
                       subject=dat$subject.length),
                  xlab="length proportion of the overlap")

Most Potrs are fully contained and fully represent the Potra A large proportion of Potrs are partial representation of the Potra A smaller proportion of Potra are contained in longer Potrs A cluster of Potra and Potrs only overlap by about 20%

comparisonplot(dat$query.length,
               dat$subject.length,
               main="Overlap proportion",
                 xlab="query",
                 ylab="subject")

Is this size related?

It is for the query where the shorter are more fully covered.

comparisonplot(log10(dat[,5] - dat[,4] + 1),
               dat$query.length,
               main="Overlap proportion relative to query size",
               ylab="query",xlim=c(1,5),
               xlab="query length (log10bp)",ylim=c(0,1))

It is for Potra, although the separation is less clear

comparisonplot(log10(dat[,14] - dat[,13] + 1),
               dat$subject.length,
               main="Overlap proportion relative to subject size",
               ylab="subject",xlim=c(1,5),
               xlab="subject length (log10bp)",ylim=c(0,1))

What about the genes located in the 20%-20% square They tend to be longer genes. It is likely that the overlap is due to them being neighbouring genes; i.e.UTR overlap

sel <- dat$query.length <= 0.2 & dat$subject.length <= 0.2

maxID <- max(as.integer(sub(".*g","",getGffAttribute(Potra.gff3,"ID"))))

Read the GMAP gff3s

gff3 <- c(readGff3("Potra01-Potrs01-mRNA.gff3.mult"),
          readGff3("Potra01-Potrs01-mRNA.gff3.transloc"),
          readGff3("Potra01-Potrs01-mRNA.gff3.uniq"))

extract the ID and Parent

IDs <- getGffAttribute(gff3,"ID")
Parent <- getGffAttribute(gff3,"Parent")

Traverse the gff3 hierarchy and collate all required IDs

ID.sel <- IDs %in% c(gIDs,
                     IDs[Parent %in% gIDs],
                     IDs[Parent %in% IDs[Parent %in% gIDs]])

sprintf("We extract %s features from a total of %s",sum(ID.sel),length(ID.sel))

3.1 Consistency check

Get the selected ID and Parents

IDs <- getGffAttribute(gff3,"ID")[,1]
Parent <- getGffAttribute(gff3,"Parent")[,1]

Collapse the hierarchy

l1 <- IDs[match(Parent,IDs)]
l2 <- Parent[match(l1,IDs)]
l2[is.na(l2)] <- ifelse(is.na(Parent[is.na(l2)]),IDs[is.na(l2)],Parent[is.na(l2)])

Check that all genes have 4 levels (gene,mRNA,exon,CDS); otherwise drop

all.feats <- sapply(lapply(split(as.character(gff3$type),l2),unique),length)
barplot(table(all.feats),main="Number of feature type per gene",sub="4 is expected")

Filter the incomplete (missing CDS) out

gff3 <- gff3[!l2 %in% names(which(all.feats!=4)),]

See if any of the remaining overlap, i.e.if the same locus has been matched several times.

grngs <- GRanges(seqnames=seq_name(gff3[gff3$type=="gene",]),
        ranges=IRanges(start=gff3[gff3$type=="gene",1],
                       end=gff3[gff3$type=="gene",2]),
        strand=strand(gff3[gff3$type=="gene",]))

ovl <- findOverlaps(grngs,ignoreSelf=TRUE,ignoreRedundant=TRUE)

Just check the connectivity of the overlap

graf <- graph.edgelist(matrix(as.character(as.matrix(ovl)),nrow=length(ovl)))
sprintf("There are %s clusters with %s members",
        clusters(graf)$no,
        length(unique(c(queryHits(ovl),subjectHits(ovl)))))
## [1] "There are 308 clusters with 732 members"
barplot(table(clusters(graf)$csize),main="clusters size")

There are quite many loci that seem redundant. Check the percentage overlap of these. It is actually obvious that these must be in all likelihood alternative splice variants, since we used all mRNAs from Potrs.

percent.ovl <- t(apply(as.matrix(ovl),1,
                     function(ro,grng){
                       g <- grng[ro]
                       (min(end(g)) - max(start(g)) + 1) / width(g)
                     },grngs))

3.2 Flatten the redundant

For those that overlap above 80%, we need to merge the gene Keep the longest coordinate for a single gene, drop all other genes, reference that only parent and list Potrs IDs in the attribute, comma sep.

graf <- graph.edgelist(matrix(
  c(getGffAttribute(gff3[gff3$type=="gene",],"ID")[queryHits(ovl)],
  getGffAttribute(gff3[gff3$type=="gene",],"ID")[subjectHits(ovl)]),
  ncol=2)[percent.ovl[,1] >= 0.8 | percent.ovl[,2] >= 0.8,])

Retrieve all coordinates

g.start <- start(grngs)
g.end <- end(grngs)
names(g.start) <- names(g.end) <- getGffAttribute(gff3[gff3$type=="gene",],"ID")

Process

red.gff <- do.call("c",mclapply(1:clusters(graf)$no,function(i,g,s,e,id,p,gff3){
                     message(i)
  # get the edges in the cluster
  nams <- get.vertex.attribute(g,"name")[which(clusters(g)$membership == i)]
  # get the sub gff
  gff <- gff3[id %in% c(nams,id[p %in% nams],id[p %in% id[p %in% nams]]),]
  
  # update the gene
  gen <- gff[gff$type=="gene",][1,]
  gen[,1] <- min(s[nams])
  gen[,2] <- max(e[nams])
  newID <- sprintf("%sg%05d",seq_name(gen),maxID + i)
  gen$gffAttributes <- sprintf("ID=%s;Name=%s;potrs=%s;confidence=Low",
                               newID,newID,
                               paste(sub("\\.path.*","",nams),
                                     collapse=","))
  
  # drop other genes
  gff <- c(gen,gff[gff$type!="gene",])
  
  # create a df to update the attributes
  df<-data.frame(ID=getGffAttribute(gff,"ID")[,1],
                 newID=getGffAttribute(gff,"ID")[,1],
                 Parent=getGffAttribute(gff,"Parent")[,1],
                 primary=FALSE,cdsMD5=NA,stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
  
  # get the CDS
  cds.grngs <- split(GRanges(seq_name(gff[gff$type=="CDS",]),
                             IRanges(start=gff[gff$type=="CDS",1],
                                     end=gff[gff$type=="CDS",2]),
                             strand=strand(gff[gff$type=="CDS",])
                             ),
                     getGffAttribute(gff[gff$type=="CDS",],"Parent"))
  
  # calc their signature
  cdsMD5 <- sapply(cds.grngs,digest)
  df[match(names(cdsMD5),df$ID),"cdsMD5"] <- cdsMD5
  
  # determine the primary and update mRNA IDs
  df[match(names(cdsMD5),df$ID),"newID"] <- paste(newID,order(
    sapply(cds.grngs,function(grng){sum(width(grng))}),
    (gff[match(names(cds.grngs),df$ID),2] - 
       gff[match(names(cds.grngs),df$ID),1] + 1),
    decreasing=TRUE),sep=".")
  df[df$newID == paste(newID,1,sep="."),"primary"] <- TRUE
  df[!is.na(df$cdsMD5),"Parent"] <- newID
  
  #  update the parents
  df$Parent <- df[match(df$Parent,df$ID),"newID"]
  
  # create the new IDs
  df[gff$type %in% c("CDS","exon"),"newID"] <- paste(
    df[gff$type %in% c("CDS","exon"),"Parent"],
    sub(".*\\.","",df[gff$type %in% c("CDS","exon"),"ID"]),
    sep=".")
  
  # update the attributes
  gff$gffAttributes[-1] <- paste("ID=",df[-1,"newID"],
                                 ";Parent=",df[-1,"Parent"],
                                 ";Name=",df[-1,"Parent"],
                                 ifelse(!is.na(df[-1,"cdsMD5"]),
                                        paste(";cdsMD5=",df[-1,"cdsMD5"],sep=""),""),
                                 ifelse(df[-1,"primary"],";primary=TRUE",""),
                                 sep="")
  
  # return
  return(gff)
  
  },graf,g.start,g.end,getGffAttribute(gff3,"ID"),
  getGffAttribute(gff3,"Parent"),gff3,mc.cores=16))

3.3 Update the non redundant

Update the max ID

maxID <- maxID + clusters(graf)$no

Re-ID

IDs <- getGffAttribute(gff3,"ID")[,1]
Parent <- getGffAttribute(gff3,"Parent")[,1]

Remove the IDs that got fixed

gIDs <- get.vertex.attribute(graf,"name")
uniq.gff <- gff3[!IDs %in% c(gIDs,
                        IDs[Parent %in% gIDs],
                        IDs[Parent %in% IDs[Parent %in% gIDs]]),]

df <- data.frame(ID=getGffAttribute(uniq.gff,"ID")[,1],
                 newID=getGffAttribute(uniq.gff,"ID")[,1],
                 Parent=getGffAttribute(uniq.gff,"Parent")[,1],
                 primary=FALSE,cdsMD5=NA,stringsAsFactors=FALSE)

Get the new gene ID

df[uniq.gff$type=="gene","newID"] <- sprintf("%sg%05d",
                                        seq_name(uniq.gff[uniq.gff$type=="gene",]),
                                        maxID + 1:sum(uniq.gff$type=="gene"))

# get the CDS
cds.grngs <- split(GRanges(seq_name(uniq.gff[uniq.gff$type=="CDS",]),
                           IRanges(start=uniq.gff[uniq.gff$type=="CDS",1],
                                   end=uniq.gff[uniq.gff$type=="CDS",2]),
                           strand=strand(uniq.gff[uniq.gff$type=="CDS",])
),getGffAttribute(uniq.gff[uniq.gff$type=="CDS",],"Parent"))

# calc their signature
cdsMD5 <- unlist(mclapply(1:length(cds.grngs),
                          function(i,g){digest(g[[i]])},cds.grngs,mc.cores=16))
df[match(names(cds.grngs),df$ID),"cdsMD5"] <- cdsMD5
df[,"primary"] <- !is.na(df[,"cdsMD5"])

#  Update the mRNA ID and Parent
df[uniq.gff$type=="mRNA","newID"] <- paste(df[match(df[uniq.gff$type=="mRNA","Parent"],
                                                    df$ID),"newID"],".1",sep="")
df[uniq.gff$type=="mRNA","Parent"] <- sub("\\.1","",df[uniq.gff$type=="mRNA","newID"])

# create the new Parent
l.parents <- df[match(df$Parent,df$ID),"newID"]
df[!is.na(l.parents),"Parent"] <- l.parents[!is.na(l.parents)]

# create the new IDs
df[uniq.gff$type %in% c("CDS","exon"),"newID"] <- paste(
  df[uniq.gff$type %in% c("CDS","exon"),"Parent"],
  sub(".*\\.","",df[uniq.gff$type %in% c("CDS","exon"),"ID"]),
  sep=".")

# update the attributes
uniq.gff$gffAttributes <- paste("ID=",df[,"newID"],
                               ifelse(!is.na(df[,"Parent"]),
                                      paste(";Parent=",df[,"Parent"],sep=""),""),
                               paste(";Name=",ifelse(!is.na(df[,"Parent"]),
                                            df[,"Parent"],
                                            df[,"newID"]),sep=""),
                               ifelse(is.na(df[,"Parent"]),
                                      paste(";potrs=",
                                            sub("\\.path.*","",df[,"ID"]),
                                            ";confidence=Low",
                                            sep=""),""),
                               ifelse(!is.na(df[,"cdsMD5"]),
                                      paste(";cdsMD5=",df[,"cdsMD5"],sep=""),""),
                               ifelse(df[,"primary"],";primary=TRUE",""),
                               sep="")

3.4 Write

We need to split the tRNA out

gff3 <- c(red.gff,uniq.gff)

3.4.1 tRNA

get the mapping ID - Parent

IDs <- getGffAttribute(gff3,"ID")[,1]
Parent <- getGffAttribute(gff3,"Parent")[,1]

if gene have grep tRNA in potrs, then fetch all ID-Parent hierarchy

tRNA.sel <- grep("tRNA",getGffAttribute(gff3[gff3$type=="gene",],"potrs"))
gIDs <- IDs[gff3$type=="gene"][tRNA.sel]

ID.sel <- IDs %in% c(gIDs,
                     IDs[Parent %in% gIDs],
                     IDs[Parent %in% IDs[Parent %in% gIDs]])

tRNA <- gff3[ID.sel,]
levels(tRNA$type) <- sub("mRNA","tRNA",levels(tRNA$type))
tRNA$type[is.na(tRNA$type)] <- "tRNA"
levels(tRNA$source) <- "PotrsMissed"
writeGff3(tRNA,file = "/mnt/picea/storage/reference/Populus-tremula/v1.0/gff3/Potra01-gene-Potrs-tRNA-low-confidence.gff3")

3.4.2 mRNA

mRNA <- gff3[!ID.sel,]
levels(mRNA$source) <- "PotrsMissed"
writeGff3(mRNA,file = "/mnt/picea/storage/reference/Populus-tremula/v1.0/gff3/Potra01-gene-Potrs-low-confidence.gff3")
